etymologies: mid 17th century (in an earlier sense). From Italian gola S-shaped moulding on a cornice, neck or entrance of a bastion, specific sense developments of gola throat from classical Latin gula

definitions: A moulding on a cornice, consisting of a continuous double curve, S-shaped in cross-section.

notes.text: "gola recta" noun a moulding in which the convex part of the profile projects beyond the concave part.
